    <h2>Critical issues — the headline findings</h2>

    <h3><span aria-hidden="true">🔴</span> Company A (the neglected one)</h3>
    <ul class="findings">
      <li><strong>The website tells every visitor the business has done zero jobs.</strong> Three "stats" counters on the homepage are broken and all render as <strong>"0&nbsp;+"</strong> — zero installs, zero repairs, zero 5-star reviews — while the top of the same page claims 70+ reviews. A potential customer sees a company advertising that it has completed nothing.</li>
      <li><strong>Three different business addresses across its own listings</strong> — three street addresses in three ZIP codes, spread across the website, a directory, and a review platform. Search engines can't confirm where this business actually is.</li>
      <li><strong>The business can't decide what it does.</strong> The logo and one social profile say gutters <em>and</em> roofing; the web address and page title say gutters only; a second social profile uses a different handle again. Search engines are told three different stories and commit to none.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3><span aria-hidden="true">🟢</span> Company B (the polished one)</h3>
    <ul class="findings">
      <li><strong>Not on the first page of search results for its own primary service, in its own city.</strong> Despite a 12-year-old web address, a modern site, and 240+ reviews, this business does not appear in the top 10 organic results. The top spots go to a national franchise, an aggregator, and several local competitors. <em>(Organic search only — the business may appear in the map/local pack, which this report doesn't measure. But missing from the main organic results is a real, fixable gap.)</em></li>
      <li><strong>Three different founding years on its own materials.</strong> The site's metadata, its body copy, and third-party directories each state a different year in the same three-year span. Small, but it's the kind of inconsistency that erodes the trust signals search engines (and customers) rely on.</li>
      <li><strong>The web address quietly expires in under 5 months.</strong> Easy to miss, expensive to forget — a lapsed domain takes the whole site, and every ranking earned over 12 years, down with it.</li>
    </ul>

