          <tr><th scope="row">Address consistent?</th><td><strong>No — 3 different addresses, 3 ZIP codes</strong></td><td>Appears consistent</td></tr>
          <tr><th scope="row">Phone consistent?</th><td>Consistent</td><td>Consistent</td></tr>
          <tr><th scope="row">Founding year consistent?</th><td>Single date</td><td><strong>No — three different years</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><th scope="row">Overall</th><td><span aria-hidden="true">🔴</span> Serious inconsistency</td><td><span aria-hidden="true">🟡</span> Minor (the founding-year drift)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2>Competitive landscape</h2>
    <p>We searched each business's primary "[service] [city]" term and looked at page 1 of the organic results.</p>
    <p><strong>Company A:</strong> Ranks <strong>#3 organically</strong> — the highest-placed <em>independent local</em> business, but sitting behind a national franchise (#1) and an online directory (#2). Being #3 in your own city means two out of every three people who search never see you first.</p>
    <p><strong>Company B:</strong> <strong>Not in the top 10 organic results</strong> for its main local search — despite being the more established, better-reviewed business. Outranked by a national franchise, an aggregator, a directory, and multiple local competitors. This is the finding that surprises confident owners the most: doing good work and having great reviews does not automatically put you on page 1.</p>

