    </div>
    <p>Company A's domain problem is quietly costly: the most obvious, searchable version of its own name belongs to a competitor. Every customer who hears the name and types the full spelling is handed to someone else.</p>

    <h2>Red flags summary</h2>

    <h3><span aria-hidden="true">🔴</span> Company A</h3>
    <ul class="findings">
      <li>Broken "0+" counters advertising zero completed jobs</li>
      <li>Three addresses / three ZIP codes across listings</li>
      <li>Conflicting identity (gutters vs. roofing) across site and social</li>
      <li>The fuller version of its name owned by a competitor</li>
      <li>Review count self-reported, not independently verified</li>
      <li>Only #3 in its own city, behind a franchise and a directory</li>
    </ul>

    <h3><span aria-hidden="true">🟡</span> Company B</h3>
    <ul class="findings">
      <li>Not on page 1 organically for its primary local search</li>
      <li>Three conflicting founding years across its own materials</li>
      <li>Domain expiring in under 5 months</li>
      <li>Headline "verified reviews" number not independently confirmed against its Google Business Profile</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What this means</h2>
    <p>Two businesses, opposite ends of the spectrum — and the Deep Dive found real, fixable, money-costing problems on both.</p>
    <p><strong>Company A</strong> is losing customers before they ever call: a site that says it's done zero jobs, an identity search engines can't pin down, and its own name pointing at a competitor.</p>
    <p><strong>Company B</strong> is the more important lesson. It does everything a good contractor is <em>supposed</em> to do — great reviews, a sharp site, decades of experience — and it still isn't on page 1 for its own core search, still has inconsistencies quietly working against it, and is one forgotten renewal away from losing 12 years of ranking. <strong>If the sharp operator has blind spots this real, so does everyone.</strong></p>
    <p>That's what the Deep Dive is for: finding the specific, checkable things costing you calls that you can't see from the inside — because you're too close to it, and because some of them (three addresses, a competitor owning your name, a rating that isn't what you think it is) are genuinely invisible unless someone goes looking.</p>

